%^RESET%^%^CYAN%^Thief:

%^RESET%^%^CYAN%^Stat requirements:%^RESET%^ 15 dexterity
%^RESET%^%^CYAN%^Races allowed:%^RESET%^ all except wemic, firbolg, ogre and half-ogre
%^RESET%^%^CYAN%^Alignments allowed:%^RESET%^ any
%^RESET%^%^CYAN%^Hitdice:%^RESET%^ d8
%^RESET%^%^CYAN%^Saving throws:%^RESET%^ reflex strong, fort/will weak
%^RESET%^%^CYAN%^Class Skills:%^RESET%^ athletics, dungeoneering, stealth, thievery
%^RESET%^%^CYAN%^Class Feats:%^RESET%^
   %^RESET%^L1: light armor proficiency, simple weapon proficiency, martial weapon proficiency, dodge
   %^RESET%^L4: combat reflexes
   %^RESET%^L7: mobility
   %^RESET%^L11: evasion
   %^RESET%^L12: tools of the trade
   %^RESET%^L14: scramble
   %^RESET%^L17: spring attack
   %^RESET%^Also: one bonus melee feat at L21, and every five class levels thereafter

The thief is the master of the shadows.  Their attacks are based on surprise, jumping from the shadows to deal great damage upon a target. %^ORANGE%^<stab>%^RESET%^ target will deal a great blow of damage to an unsuspecting foe, dependent on the thief's stealth. They can also %^ORANGE%^<spy>%^RESET%^ on a target to assess their belongings, hopefully without being noticed.

Thieves can use nothing heavier than light armor types, as they rely on speed and stealth. Various skills and commands will either take a penalty when wearing metal armor, or will simply not work at all. A high dexterity is very important and useful to thieves.

Major part of thieves play is interaction with thieves guilds across the realms. Hidden within cities, they provide additional services, such as fencing and unique combat supplies.

Thieves rely on learning melee feats to expand their options in combat.

%^RESET%^%^CYAN%^See also: %^RESET%^ feats, stats, skills, stab, stealth, prestige classes

